00:19:33.450 --> 00:19:36.400
So if you're building a service
that involves map

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:39.440
points, points of interest, you
probably want to look at

00:19:39.440 --> 00:19:40.400
something like Fusion Tables.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.540
It's going to serve your
needs really well.

00:19:42.540 --> 00:19:45.830
Now, on the other hand, this
leaves Spreadsheets and

00:19:45.830 --> 00:19:48.600
ScriptDb, when to use one,
when to use the other.

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:52.140
I've been using Spreadsheets
a lot these last few days,

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:54.070
mostly because you get
a couple of benefits.

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:55.700
You get a built-in UI.

00:19:55.700 --> 00:19:56.920
You get a ton of features.

00:19:56.920 --> 00:19:59.080
You get sorting, filtering.

00:19:59.080 --> 00:20:00.810
You can add charts
very easily.

00:20:00.810 --> 00:20:01.530
ARUN NAGARAJAN: Versioning.

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:02.340
IKAI LAN: Yeah.

00:20:02.340 --> 00:20:03.470
You get versioning?

00:20:03.470 --> 00:20:04.010
ARUN NAGARAJAN: Versioning.

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:04.260
IKAI LAN: Right, right.

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:05.730
I actually never check
the version.

00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:07.360
Because there's too
many edits.

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:09.810
ARUN NAGARAJAN: It does become
a lot of versions.

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:12.240
IKAI LAN: But Spreadsheets
has a very nice UI.

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:14.420
Now again, the downside is
something I mentioned earlier,

00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:17.050
which is, because it has UI, if
you give it to people, you

00:20:17.050 --> 00:20:21.780
give them a chance to
really break things.

00:20:21.780 --> 00:20:24.130
So that's Spreadsheets.

00:20:24.130 --> 00:20:27.550
ScriptDb, on the other hand,
is kind of neat, because

00:20:27.550 --> 00:20:30.720
ScriptDb is, if you have a
single instance of a script,

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.310
you have a global ScriptDb
instance that's shared for all

00:20:33.310 --> 00:20:34.110
users of the script.

00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:36.670
Now, you might be asking, why
would I want to do this?

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:39.000
You can technically also do this
via Spreadsheets if you

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.210
open a spreadsheet via ID.

00:20:41.210 --> 00:20:44.010
The difference is that there's
no UI for ScriptDb.

00:20:44.010 --> 00:20:47.170
The filter semantics and the
objects you can save in

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:50.080
ScriptDb tend to be a little
bit more robust.

00:20:50.080 --> 00:20:53.660
They look closer to JavaScript
objects.

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:55.190
And you've got a little
bit better

00:20:55.190 --> 00:20:57.060
programmatic query language.

00:20:57.060 --> 00:21:03.150
Like you can say show me all
the people that have an age

00:21:03.150 --> 00:21:05.520
greater than 45.

00:21:05.520 --> 00:21:08.010
And that's much easier in
ScriptDb, whereas if you were

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:09.320
to do this in--

00:21:09.320 --> 00:21:11.240
I think you should be able to
filter in Spreadsheets but

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:13.210
it's not quite as intuitive--

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:14.740
you get a few other
things in ScriptDb

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:15.740
that are kind of neat.

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:19.630
But again, also appending to
Spreadsheets, you pretty much

00:21:19.630 --> 00:21:21.540
only can append in
a row format.

00:21:21.540 --> 00:21:23.230
With ScriptDb, you can actually

00:21:23.230 --> 00:21:24.640
have embedded objects.

00:21:24.640 --> 00:21:25.260
ARUN NAGARAJAN: Right.

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:26.400
And they can be jagged.

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:28.420
So one object can look
in one shape.

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:30.340
Another object could be
completely different.

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:32.880
And then you can actually have
them all in the same bucket.

00:21:32.880 --> 00:21:35.850
So it gives you a lot more
capability as far as the type

00:21:35.850 --> 00:21:36.840
of things you store.

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:37.340
IKAI LAN: Right.

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:40.110
The only thing about storing
objects of different types and

00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:42.640
different shapes is that,
try to keep them fairly

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:43.350
consistent.

00:21:43.350 --> 00:21:46.690
Now, I don't like it when
it's too rigid.

00:21:46.690 --> 00:21:48.370
But if you keep it consistent,
like you have

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:49.170
three or four types--

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:49.490
ARUN NAGARAJAN: For indexing.

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:51.490
IKAI LAN: --in your program,
it's going to be that crazy.

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:53.750
If every single object that
you store looks totally

00:21:53.750 --> 00:21:56.780
different, you're not going
to be able to do anything.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:21:58.070
You're going to drive
yourself nuts.

00:21:58.070 --> 00:22:02.190
