00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:34.090
And when UIs start to get a
little more complex, there's

00:25:34.090 --> 00:25:38.130
something called the model
view presenter pattern.

00:25:38.130 --> 00:25:39.600
I'm not going to overly
advocate it.

00:25:39.600 --> 00:25:43.200
But the idea is that in code
that you use to build the UI,

00:25:43.200 --> 00:25:45.530
try to make this as simple
as possible.

00:25:45.530 --> 00:25:48.100
And what you do is, you want
to abstract out some more

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:50.620
complex bits into these
functions that can run without

00:25:50.620 --> 00:25:51.395
UI components.

00:25:51.395 --> 00:25:54.510
So an example is, this thing
I'm building for URL

00:25:54.510 --> 00:25:55.370
shortening, for instance.

00:25:55.370 --> 00:25:57.210
I have a UI that pops up,
just asks you for a

00:25:57.210 --> 00:25:59.830
URL and some options.

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:01.870
It has a place that calls
a URL shortener.

00:26:01.870 --> 00:26:04.880
Now, in the beginning, I just
tested it as is, where I put

00:26:04.880 --> 00:26:07.190
all the code in one function,
built the UI, built the

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:07.950
handler, whatever.

00:26:07.950 --> 00:26:11.150
And I was testing it like
running the code in the UI,

00:26:11.150 --> 00:26:12.530
pushing the buttons, seeing
if it worked.

00:26:12.530 --> 00:26:14.060
And after a while this
got too hard.

00:26:14.060 --> 00:26:16.970
So instead, I took the URL
shortening part, which isn't

00:26:16.970 --> 00:26:18.790
